th index 3.\nThe resulting string is \"[[]]\".\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: s = \"]]][[[\"\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: You can do the following to make the string balanced:\n- Swap index 0 with index 4. s = \"[]][][\".\n- Swap index 1 with index 5. s = \"[[][]]\".\nThe resulting string is \"[[][]]\".\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: s = \"[]\"\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: The string is already balanced.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\nn == s.length\n2 <= n <= 106\nn is even.\ns[i] is either '[' or ']'.\nThe number of opening brackets '[' equals n / 2, and the number of closing brackets ']' equals n / 2.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minSwaps(self, s: str) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minSwaps(self, s: str) -> int:\n        x = 0\n        for c in s:\n            if c == \"[\":\n                x += 1\n            elif x:\n                x -= 1\n        return (x + 1) >> 1\n```\n\nThis solution works by maintaining a counter `x` that tracks the balance of opening and closing brackets. As we iterate through the string:\n- We increment `x` for each opening bracket `[`.\n- We decrement `x` for each closing bracket `]` only if `x` is positive (indicating there is a matching opening bracket).\n- At the end of the iteration, `x` will represent the number of unmatched closing brackets (excess of `]` over `[`). The minimum number of swaps needed to balance the string is half of this value, rounded up. This is achieved by `(x + 1) >> 1`, which is equivalent to `(x + 1) // 2`.", "estimated_date": 1628380800000}